A method reference is a short-hand for lambda expressions that call an existing method.

ðŸ‘‰ Syntax:

ClassName::methodName
Types of Method References
1. Static Method Reference
ClassName::staticMethod


Example

Function<Integer, Integer> f = Math::abs;


Equivalent lambda:

n -> Math.abs(n)

2. Instance Method Reference (Object)
object::instanceMethod


Example

Consumer<String> c = System.out::println;

Equivalent lambda:
s -> System.out.println(s)

3. Instance Method Reference (Class)
ClassName::instanceMethod


Example
BiFunction<String, String, Boolean> eq =
        String::equals;
Equivalent lambda:
(a, b) -> a.equals(b)





package methodreference;

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class MethodReferences {
    public static void print(String s){
        System.out.println(s);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> students = Arrays.asList("Alice,Bob,Wasif,John");
       // students.forEach(s-> System.out.println(s));
        //replace lambda with method reference
       // students.forEach(System.out::println); // using method reference
        students.forEach(MethodReferences::print);
    }

}
